  "text": "anchor Poster courtesy of adamymotherthearchitect.com If you’re in the New York City area on Friday, May 9th, be sure not to miss the premiere of Yael Melamede‘s new documentary ADA: My Mother The Architect depicting the life of the late Ada Karmi-Melamede at the Angelika Film Center.  Karmi-Melamede’s work in Israel and New York, where she was denied tenure at the Columbia GSAPP in the 1980s. It joins a string of documentaries produced by Jim Venturi, Nathaniel Kahn, Tomas Koolhaas, and other children of famous architects, offering a glimpse into Karmi-Melamede’s career while it \"raises timely questions about the cost of success and the legacy we leave behind.\" A second screening will take place at the Laemmle Royal in Los Angeles on May 16th for West Coast viewers. Video courtesy Salty Features Similar articles on Archinect that may interest you... 'E.1027 – Eileen Gray and the House by the Sea' captures the famous architectural drama in a new docufiction New documentary captures Eliot Noyes' profound influence on American corporate life and design 'Schindler Space Architect' documentary premieres in Los Angeles Documentary exposes harsh labor conditions and deaths at NEOM’s The Line Influential 1970s women architects exhibition revisited in new Beverly Willis Architecture Foundation series Filmmaker Kevin Siyuan releases final ‘A Wes Anderson-ish Singapore’ update",
